  "doc_id": "9232",
  "text": "The procedure for identifying funnels on the TSP has evolved in recent work, ranging from visual inspection of the fitness distance correlation plots [CITATION_1] , con-nected components in the local optima networks [CITATION_2] , and 3D LON visualisation [CITATION_3] . We propose here to use the notion of monotonic sequences from theoretical chemistry [CITATION_4] , which describes a sequence of local minima where the energy of minima is always decreasing. We adapt this notion to the context of fitness landscapes and consider a monotonic sequence as a sequence of local optima where the fitness (costs) of solutions is non-deteriorating. The set of monotonic sequences leading to a particular optimum has been termed 'basin' [CITATION_5] , 'monotonic sequence basin' [CITATION_6] and 'super-basins' [CITATION_7] , in the theoretical chemistry literature. We chose here to call them 'funnel basins' or simply 'funnels' borrowing from the protein folding literature. We can distinguish the primary funnel, as the one involving monotonic sequences that terminate at the global optimum (there can be more than one). The primary funnel is separated from other neighbouring secondary funnels by transition states laying on a so-called 'primary divide' [CITATION_8] . Above such a divide, it is possible for a local optima to belong to more than one funnel through different monotonic sequences.",
